\fs30 \cf2 On a June day after the 2021 spring semester, the 20-year-old college student swallowed a bottle of pills at her off-campus apartment.\
\
As she slowly woke up at the emergency room in New Haven, Conn., one thought overwhelmed her: \'93What if Yale finds out?\'94\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 She\'92d heard about other students being forced to leave because of depression and suicidal thoughts, and about the lengthy, nerve-racking reapplication process. It was one reason that the student \'97 whom The Post agreed to identify by her first initial, S., to protect her privacy \'97 told only a few people about her problems.\
\
Three months earlier, a Yale freshman named\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://yaledailynews.com/blog/2021/03/24/she-was-unapologetically-herself-communities-mourn-rachael-shaw-rosenbaum-class-of24/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \strokec3 Rachael Shaw-Rosenbaum}}\'a0had killed herself on campus after contemplating the consequences of withdrawing from the school, her family said. Her death had renewed fierce debate about campus mental health, the way Yale treated suicidal students and the university\'92s reinstatement policies. Similar controversies have engulfed other universities as student mental health problems soar across the country.\
\
Confined to a room at Yale New Haven Psychiatric Hospital, S. asked her nurses and doctors with growing fear, \'93Do you have to tell them?\'94\

\fs32 \

\fs30 Yes, they replied. Because she was a student, hospital staffers said, they needed to let college officials know, she recalled. They gave her consent papers to sign for the release of her medical information. She remembers how vulnerable she felt in her thin hospital clothes as she signed the release.\
\
The hospital declined to comment on her account, citing patient confidentiality.\
\
Yale officials quickly set up a Zoom call with S. on a hospital laptop in a small, bare room. On the screen, she said, was Paul Hoffman, the psychologist in charge of student mental health at Yale.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1 \cf2 She told him about the rape she\'92d experienced \'97 but had never reported because she didn\'92t want her parents to know \'97 and how it had sent her spiraling into suicidal thoughts.\
\
He nodded and took notes. A few days later, he arranged a second Zoom call, with her and her parents.\
\
\'93We\'92re going to recommend you take a medical withdrawal,\'94 he told her, she said.\
\
\'93Do I have to?\'94 S. remembers asking him.\
\
\'93We\'92re going to strongly recommend it,\'94 Hoffman replied.\
\
In an interview, Hoffman and other Yale officials declined to discuss Yale\'92s withdrawal policies or specific student cases. After Shaw-Rosenbaum\'92s suicide, the university told\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://yaledailynews.com/blog/2021/03/29/students-express-grievances-over-yales-medical-withdrawal-policies/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \strokec3 the Yale Daily News}}
\f2\b \'a0
\f1\b0 that
\f2\b \'a0
\f1\b0 involuntary withdrawals from Yale are rare and that the majority
\f2\b \'a0
\f1\b0 of students who apply for reinstatement are allowed to return.\
\
For S., leaving Yale meant losing her friends and mentors \'97 people who had kept her afloat during her depression. It meant losing her routine, her lab research, her four-year plan to get into medical school. Losing all the things that gave her purpose, identity and support when she needed them most.\
\
S. had followed the campus debate in the wake of Shaw-Rosenbaum\'92s suicide. She knew Yale could force her to withdraw if she didn\'92t leave on her own.\
\
As soon as the Zoom call with Hoffman ended, hospital staffers handed her the cellphone they\'92d taken when she arrived. She began typing out the email Hoffman had asked her to send. \'93Good afternoon,\'94 it read. \'93I am requesting a medical withdrawal.\'94\
\
In coming months, S. would look back to that moment with anger and regret. It wasn\'92t what she imagined when she was admitted to Yale, one of the country\'92s most prestigious universities. She recalled how her family screamed for joy. How special she felt when Yale found out Brown and Northwestern had also accepted her and raised her financial aid to match what they would provide.\
\
\'93They make you feel like you\'92re the best of the best, like this bright and shiny thing,\'94 she said. \'93But as soon as something\'92s wrong, they want nothing to do with you.\'94\
\
It had been difficult
\f2\b \'a0
