\f3\b\fs48 \cf2 \'91Getting rid of me\'92\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs30 \cf2 Five years before the pandemic derailed so many college students\'92 lives, a 20-year-old math major named Luchang Wang posted this message on Facebook:\
\
\'93Dear Yale, I loved being here. I only wish I could\'92ve had some time. I needed time to work things out and to wait for new medication to kick in, but I couldn\'92t do it in school, and I couldn\'92t bear the thought of having to leave for a full year, or of leaving and never being readmitted. Love, Luchang.\'94\
\
Wang had withdrawn from Yale once before and feared that under Yale\'92s policies, a second readmission could be denied.
\fs32 \
\

\fs30 Instead, she flew to San Francisco, and, according to authorities, climbed over the railing at the Golden Gate Bridge and jumped to her death.\
\
Her 2015 suicide sparked
\f4\b \'a0
\f0\b0 demands for change at Yale. Administrators convened a committee to evaluate readmission policies, but critics said the reforms they adopted were minor.\
\
They renamed the process \'93reinstatement\'94 instead of \'93readmission,\'94 eliminated a $50 reapplication fee and gave students a few more days at the beginning of each semester to take a leave of absence without having to reapply.\
\
Students who withdrew still needed to write an essay, secure letters of recommendation, interview with Yale officials and prove their academic worth by taking two courses at another four-year university. Those who left for mental health reasons also had to\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://yalecollege.yale.edu/policies-procedures/reinstatement-faq"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \strokec3 demonstrate to Yale}}\'a0that they\'92d addressed their problems.\
\
In April \'97 nearly 10 months after S. had been pressured to withdraw \'97 Yale officials announced another round of changes to the reinstatement process. They eliminated the requirement that students pass two courses at another university and got rid of a mandatory interview with the reinstatement committee.\
\
The reforms have not satisfied student activists at Yale, where the mental health problems playing out\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.washingtonpost.com/parenting/2022/11/08/college-mental-health-parents/?itid=lk_inline_manual_37"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \strokec3 on many American campuses}}\'a0have been especially prominent.\
\
When students are in crisis, their universities often face dueling pressures: the threat of being sued by families if a student dies by suicide, but also accusations of discrimination against those with mental disabilities if that student is forced to leave.\
\
\'93Sometimes students do need help and do need time off,\'94 said Karen Bower, a lawyer who has represented more than 100 college students forced to take mental health withdrawals. \'93But colleges are also becoming more aware that they can\'92t just push students out.\'94\
\
Yale has been slower than some elite universities to accommodate students who don\'92t want to leave, critics said.\
\
In recent years, Yale has also faced an \'93explosion\'94 in demand for mental health counseling, university officials said. Last year, roughly 5,000 Yale students sought treatment \'97 a 90 percent increase compared with 2015.\
\
\'93It\'92s like nothing we\'92ve ever seen before,\'94 said Hoffman,
\f4\b \'a0
\f0\b0 the director of Yale Mental Health and Counseling. Roughly 34 percent of the 14,500 students at Yale seek mental health help from college counselors, compared with a national average of\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.aucccd.org/assets/2020-21%20Annual%20Survey%20Report%20Public%20Survey.pdf"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \strokec3 11 percent}}\'a0at other universities.\
\
Meeting that need has been challenging, even at a school with a $41.4 billion endowment.\
\
Bluebelle Carroll, 20, a Yale sophomore who sought help in September 2021, said she waited six months to be assigned a therapist. She secured her first appointment only after emailing the counseling staff repeatedly.\
\
\'93The appointment was 20 minutes long,\'94 she said, \'93and we spent the last five minutes figuring out when he could see me again.\'94\
\
Because of staffing constraints, students are often asked to choose between weekly therapy that lasts 30 minutes or 45-minute sessions every two weeks.\
\
\'93It actually made things worse,\'94 said Shayna Sragovicz, 22, a senior. \'93Because you\'92re opening up a can of worms in people\'92s psyche and then not giving them space to work through them.\'94\
\
In the past year, Yale officials said, the university has hired six more counselors for a total of more than 50. It now allows students to join group therapy sessions in addition to individual counseling. It also added support staffers and launched a pilot program called YC3, where students can drop in for short-term counseling.\
\
The new hires have reduced wait times, Hoffman said. Most students are now able to get therapy appointments within two weeks, he said, and the university hopes to hire more counselors.\
\
\'93Yale has made a very significant commitment to resources for mental health,\'94 he said.\
\
But many students and former students tell a different story. In interviews, more than 25 described a university flush with money, yet beset by inadequate services and policies that often fail students in crisis.\
\
Some described never hearing back from Yale counselors after seeking help. Others said they\'92ve learned to hide mental problems and suicidal thoughts to avoid triggering withdrawal policies that they believe are designed to protect Yale from lawsuits and damage to its reputation.\
\
\'93It\'92s the exact opposite of what you\'92d want to happen,\'94 said Miriam Kopyto, 22, a senior and a leader in the Yale Student Mental Health Association.\
\
Several students recounted being given 72 hours or less to leave campus once they withdrew.\
\
Nicolette M\'e1ntica was already seeing a Yale therapist as a junior in 2017 when a residential dean learned she periodically cut her arms to cope with stress. That night, the dean invited her to a meeting without telling her why, she said.\
\
She was transported to Yale\'92s hospital, where college officials told her she had no choice but to withdraw. When she was discharged, a campus police officer escorted her to her dorm room and gave her two hours to pack everything and leave, she said.\
\
\'93It was just me and my parents throwing all my things into any bag we could find. I was running up and down the stairs sobbing while the officer watched us,\'94 she said. \'93It wasn\'92t about helping me. It was about getting rid of me.\'94\
\
Seven months later, in the middle of applying for reinstatement, Mantica tried to kill herself.\
\
As she recovered in a hospital in her home state of Georgia, she asked herself why she was so fixated on a university that had abandoned her. She decided to transfer
\f4\b \'a0
\f0\b0 to Northwestern University.\
\
\'93Why go through all the work and struggle to get back to a place where they didn\'92t care about me?\'94 she said. \'93Where I felt like a criminal for struggling with mental health?\'94\
\
University officials did not respond to questions about their interactions with Mantica, S. or any of the other students quoted in this story.\
