\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs30 \cf2 For days, the essay sat blank on her laptop. She added her name, then a title, \'93Application for Reinstatement,\'94 but couldn\'92t go further.\
\
It had taken her weeks to write her first admission essay to Yale, detailing her passion for dance and volunteer work.\
\
This time, however, the prompt was starker: 500 to 750 words explaining her withdrawal, what she\'92d done with the year off and why she felt ready to return.\
\
But S. was still angry about being exiled from Yale. She kept replaying the conversation she\'92d had with the officials who insisted she withdraw.\
\
\'93They never asked what they could do to help with the sexual assault and PTSD. Not a single question about how Yale can support you. They didn\'92t take into account who I was and what I needed,\'94 she said. \'93Their only concern was that I leave.\'94\
\
Now the only remaining signs of her connection to the university were a Yale hoodie, a Yale-emblazoned wallet she\'92d bought as a freshman and a sticker with the university\'92s \'93Y\'94 logo on the back of her laptop.\
\
S. knew all the resentment had no place in her reapplication essay. So it sat blank, until one evening in May, when she banged out the whole thing in a few hours.\
\
She wrote in matter-of-fact language about how she\'92d sought therapy to deal with the PTSD from her sexual assault. She included a line about her work with domestic violence victims and international students.\
\
\'93I am extremely proud of myself and my progress,\'94 she concluded. \'93I feel more ready than ever to be a student at Yale, and I sincerely hope to have the opportunity to do so again.\'94\
\
A few days after she sent it in, she found herself staring at the \'93Y\'94 sticker on her laptop and ripped it off. She emptied out her Yale wallet and threw it away. She knew she wouldn\'92t hear back about the reinstatement committee\'92s decision for another two months.\
\
\'93I\'92ve done everything they asked,\'94 she said. \'93If the objective truth isn\'92t enough, if they don\'92t think I\'92m worthy, then Yale isn\'92t where I should be.\'94\
\
