\f3\b\fs48 \cf2 \'91I needed help\'92\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs30 \cf2 In 2018, researchers at the Ruderman Foundation, which advocates for the disabled, assessed the mental health withdrawal policies at all eight Ivy League schools. No university received a grade above D+, and Yale received an F.\
\
Since then, several Ivy League colleges have reformed their policies, often in response to\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/10/08/stanford-changes-leave-policies-mental-illness"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \strokec3 high-profile lawsuits}}\'a0or\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.concordmonitor.com/Dartmouth-begins-fall-term-amid-news-of-student-deaths-48279784"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \strokec3 deaths}}. And every Ivy except Yale and Brown has joined
\f4\b \'a0
\f0\b0 a four-year-long program to improve its mental health policies through the Jed Foundation, a nonprofit organization focused on suicide prevention and mental health for teens and young adults.\
\
More than 400 colleges have
\f4\b \'a0
\f0\b0 enrolled in the Jed program, said Nance Roy, the foundation\'92s chief clinical officer, who also works as an assistant psychiatry professor at Yale.\
\
\'93I\'92m not sure why Yale hasn\'92t joined,\'94 Roy said. \'93I\'92ve had conversations with them, and even met with the president and others at one point about it. I don\'92t think they\'92re ignoring the issue. But they\'92re doing their own thing.\'94\
\
In a written statement, Yale spokeswoman Karen Peart said, \'93The College engages in frequent evaluation of all its policies in an effort to best serve our students.\'94\
\
Over the past year, Yale has been under increasing pressure to reform its reinstatement process.\
\
\'93It\'92s hard to explain what\'92s so dehumanizing about it that it\'92s haunted me for two decades,\'94 said Alicia Floyd, who withdrew after a suicide attempt in 2000 and now works as a doctor. \'93It\'92s the betrayal you feel, the violation. Realizing how unimportant you are to this institution that you had such high hopes for. The trauma of how they treated me has outlasted many other issues I had.\'94\
\
After Shaw-Rosenbaum\'92s death, Floyd and other alumni created a nonprofit group called\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.elisforrachael.org/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \strokec3 Elis for Rachael}}. They\'92ve held a campus vigil for suicide prevention and given money and guidance to students navigating reapplication.\
\
They\'92ve also demanded that Yale administrators change their approach to students in mental crisis.\
\
Instead of the all-or-nothing proposition of withdrawal, they say students should be given options such as reducing course loads or attending part-time.\
\
Many schools have stopped forcing
\f4\b \'a0
\f0\b0 students to withdraw and have lowered barriers for them to return. Three years ago, Stanford University settled a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://stanforddaily.com/2019/10/07/stanford-to-overhaul-leave-of-absence-policies-in-watershed-class-action-settlement/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \strokec3 class-action lawsuit}}\'a0by agreeing to give students greater say in whether to take a leave of absence for mental health reasons. And if students choose to remain, the university now provides disability accommodations. Last year,\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/justice-department-reaches-agreement-brown-university-ensure-equal-access-students-mental"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \strokec3 Brown University\'a0}}agreed to changes following an investigation by the U.S. Justice Department.\
\
At Duke University, students who take time off now have\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://undergrad.duke.edu/student-success/time-away-office/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \strokec3 an office}}\'a0dedicated to supporting them while they are away. Boston University\'92s Center for Psychiatric Rehabilitation created a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://cpr.bu.edu/cmhep/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \strokec3 program}}\'a0and a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://rudermanfoundation.org/white_papers/leave-of-absence/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \strokec3 48-page guide}}\'a0to help college students navigate leaves of absence.\
\
Yale\'92s activists note that students forced to withdraw lose their student health insurance and access to counseling when they need those benefits most.\
\
\'93My big question was how do I get therapy,\'94 said Alicia Abramson, 22, a current student who withdrew in her sophomore year while struggling with depression and an eating disorder. \'93Once you\'92re out, they cut you off from everything. I couldn\'92t afford therapy on my own. My family didn\'92t believe I had mental problems at first and didn\'92t want to pay for it. I had to have a breakdown and almost kill myself before I got the help I needed.\'94\
\
She and other students say that despite increased staffing, Yale\'92s mental health services still lag behind demand.\
\
Madison Hahamy, the student reporter who\'92d talked to Shaw-Rosenbaum about her depression for the Yale Daily News, was haunted by her suicide.\
\
\'93She was so vulnerable and raw with me,\'94 Hahamy said.\
\
Months later, Hahamy found herself struggling as well. In September 2021, she talked to a counselor through the new YC3 program. The counselor asked whether Hahamy ever had suicidal thoughts.\
\
\'93She was the first person I\'92d ever told that to,\'94 said Hahamy, now 22 and a junior. \'93I was crying every single night. I needed help.\'94\
\
But it took two months and repeated requests for her to get an appointment with a therapist, she said. After a few months of 30-minute sessions
\f4\b \'a0
\f0\b0 every other week, Hahamy stopped going.\
\
\'93It was so short, it was just making me feel worse,\'94 she said. \'93Even after everything that happened to Rachael, it\'92s like nothing changed.\'94\
